FERC ELECTRIC RATE SCHEDULE
NO. 1
OF
NEW ENGLAND HYDRO-TRANSMISSION ELECTRIC COMPANY, INC.
Filed with the
FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION
Replacement of the Phase II High Voltage Direct Current Controls and Protection Systems at the Radisson, Nicolet and Sandy Pond Converter Stations This Agreement regarding the Replacement of the Phase II High Voltage Direct Current ("HVDC") Controls and Protection Systems at the Radisson, Nicolet and Sandy Pond Converter Stations (the "Agreement"), is made as of the ____ day of July, 2013, between New England Hydro-Transmission Electric Company, Inc. ("National Grid") and Hydro-Qubec Transnergie ("HQ Transnergie") (each a "Party", and collectively, the "Parties"). WHEREAS, the New England Asset Owners and HQ Transnergie are parties to an Asset Owners Agreement dated November 29, 2011 ("AOA") by which they can undertake and coordinate any joint upgrade on the Interconnection Facilities; WHEREAS, National Grid owns the Sandy Pond Converter Terminal, rated for 2,000 MW and located near Ayer, Massachusetts (the "Sandy Pond Converter Station"); WHEREAS, HQ Transnergie owns the Radisson Converter Terminal, rated for 2,250 MW and located at the LaGrande River in the James Bay region of Quebec (the "Radisson Converter Station") and the Nicolet Converter Terminal, rated for 2,138 MW located approximately 40 miles north of Sherbrooke, Qubec (the "Nicolet Converter Station"); WHEREAS, the Parties have identified a need based on asset condition to replace the HVDC control and protection systems at the Radisson, Nicolet and Sandy Pond Converter Stations; WHEREAS, the Parties desire to cooperate in the planning, conceptual engineering, vendor selection, implementation, and commissioning of the replacement of the Phase II HVDC control and protection systems at the Radisson, Nicolet and Sandy Pond Converter Stations (the "Project"); WHEREAS, the Parties desire to set forth in this Agreement their respective rights and obligations in connection with the Project in accordance with and subject to the terms and conditions of the AOA; NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises contained herein and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows:
ARTICLE 1 DEFINITIONS When used in this Agreement with initial capitalization, the following terms shall have the following meanings. Terms used in this Agreement with initial capitalization that are not defined in this Article 1 or in any other Article of this Agreement shall have the meaning specified in the AOA. 1.1 Decisions shall mean determinations in connection with the Project which are required under the Asset Owners Agreement or under the terms of this Agreement to be made by the Asset Owners Committee. 1.2 Effective Date shall have the meaning set forth in Section 3.1 of this Agreement. 1.3 Fundamental Project Decisions shall mean decisions proposed by a Party relating to the Project which may be reasonably expected to materially affect the scope, schedule, or cost of the Project and impact the other Party, and shall include, but not be limited to those decisions outlined in Article 5 hereof. 1.4 Governmental Authorities shall mean any nation, state, sovereign or government, any federal, regional or state, local, or political subdivision or agency, or any entity exercising executive, legislative, judicial, regulatory or administrative functions of or pertaining to government. Governmental Authorities includes, without limitation, the FERC and the Rgie de l'nergie. 1.5 Project Approvals shall mean any authorizations, consents, approvals, licenses or permits issued or granted by any Governmental Authority or the ISO which are necessary or advisable to be obtained for or in connection with the Project, or any part thereof, during the term of this Agreement. 1.6 Project Manager shall have the meaning specified in Section 4.1.1 of this Agreement. 1.7 Sandy Pond, Radisson and Nicolet Converter Stations shall have the meaning identified in the preamble to this Agreement and in Attachment 1 of the Asset Owners Agreement. 1.8 Segment: shall mean for National Grid the portion of the Project located in the State of Massachusetts and for HQ Transnergie the portion of the Project located in the province of Qubec, Canada. 1.9 Shared Costs shall have the meaning specified in Section 7.2.1 of this Agreement.
ARTICLE 2 PURPOSE OF AGREEMENT 2.1 Purpose. In order to maintain the reliability, operability, and Nominal Transfer Capability of the Interconnection Facilities, the purpose of this Agreement is to coordinate replacements of the associated control and protection systems at the Converter Stations as specified in the terms of this Agreement. 2.2 Project Activities. Activities associated with the Project shall consist of, but not be limited to, the following: * Description of works of the Interconnection Facilities controls and protection system * Choice of contractors/suppliers and purchase of equipment * Implementation of scope, schedule, timeline, in-service date * Design, selection and installation * Commencement of installation of the replacements of the Phase II HVDC control and protection systems at the Radisson, Nicolet and Sandy Pond Converter Stations * Identification of proposed shared costs (e.g.IREQ testing) * Identifying and making Fundamental Project Decisions * Scheduling outages, conducting applicable tests and communicating test results ARTICLE 3 EFFECTIVE DATE AND TERMINATION 3.1 Effective Date. This Agreement shall become effective as of the date first written above, subject to its approval or acceptance for filing by the FERC. 3.2 Term. This Agreement shall remain in full force and effect until performance has been completed hereunder and final accounting (including payment of any amounts due) has been completed as contemplated by Section 7.8 of this Agreement. 3.3 Termination. This Agreement may be terminated at any time by written mutual agreement of the Parties, subject to Article 7 and Article 8 of this Agreement.
ARTICLE 4
MANAGEMENT OF THE PROJECT
4.1 Project Management Generally.
4.1.1. Each Party shall appoint a project manager (each, a "Project Manager") who shall be responsible for the Project management of such Party's Segment, including establishing a budget and a schedule and using good faith to obtain Project Approvals for its Segment. 4.1.2 In order for any decision or approval contemplated by this Agreement to be effective, such decision or approval must be agreed to (i) by both Project Managers, (ii) by the AOC, but only if and to the extent AOC approval is contemplated by Section 4.2 of this Agreement, and (iii) if such decision or approval is outside the limited authority of the Project Managers as set forth in Section 4.4, by both Parties. Decisions or approvals by Project Managers shall be made in their respective reasonable discretion, and shall be evidenced by a written instrument signed by each such Project Manager. 4.2 Role of the Asset Owners Committee. 4.2.1 The AOC is authorized, among other things, to do all things necessary and reasonable to ensure that the Parties carry out the AOA. The role of the AOC in connection with the Project shall be to: 4.2.1.1 Approve any Fundamental Project Decisions; 4.2.1.2 Receive reports and request additional information from the Project Managers in order to measure progress in achieving the Project milestones and to recommend corrective action if necessary; 4.2.1.3 Assist in the resolution of disputes between the Project Managers or the Parties in accordance with Article 13 of the AOA; and 4.2.1.4 Determine cost allocations in connection with the Project to the extent required by Section 5.10 or Section 7.2(i) of the AOA. 4.3 Role of the Project Managers. Each Project Manager: 4.3.1 Shall work cooperatively with the other Project Manager in order to promote achievement of the objectives of this Agreement, including implementation of the Project; 4.3.2 Shall make available to the other Project Manager any and all information reasonably requested that is not privileged, proprietary or confidential concerning those aspects of the Project that do not affect the interests of the other Party.
4.3.3 Shall, together with the other Project Manager, establish estimated progress milestones, and develop measurement tools and protocols applicable thereto, to monitor the implementation of the Project. 4.3.4 Shall, together with the other Project Manager, meet with the AOC during the AOC's scheduled or special meetings to: (i) Report on the progress of the activities relating to the Project, including without limitation, any material changes to scope, schedule or cost of the Project; and (ii) Present to the AOC those matters contemplated by Section 4.2.1 and Article 5 of this Agreement. 4.3.5 Each Party's Project Manager shall have the responsibility for taking all administrative actions with respect to any Project-related item on the agenda of any AOC meeting relating to such Party's Segment. 4.4 Limited Authority for Project Managers. Neither Party shall be working on or accessing the facilities of the other Party in connection with performance under this Agreement. Neither Project Manager shall have any authority to amend, supplement or otherwise modify the terms of this Agreement or the AOA, waive any provision thereof, or commit any Party to pay any Shared Costs. ARTICLE 5 FUNDAMENTAL PROJECT DECISIONS 5.1 Fundamental Project Decisions Generally. Fundamental Project Decisions shall include, but not be limited to: 5.1.1 Review and approval of the outage schedule in connection with the Project; and 5.1.2. Review and approval of the final testing and commissioning plan for the Project. 5.1.3 Establishment of any major strategy or public relations position affecting the Project.
ARTICLE 6
RESPONSIBILITIES OF THE PARTIES
6.1 Filings and Approvals. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, and unless otherwise agreed by the Parties, each Party shall have the responsibility for drafting and prosecuting all applications for approval by Governmental Authorities associated with its Segment of the Project.
6.2 Engineering Review. 6.2.1 Each Party shall be responsible for the preparation and review of all engineering for its Segment of the Project. The Parties shall use reasonable efforts to coordinate with each other to ensure that their respective design, milestones and operating criteria with respect to the Project are compatible. 6.2.2 Each Party shall furnish promptly to the other Party, all data, drawings and other documents necessary for engineering reviews of the compatibility of the Project as may be reasonably requested by the other Party. 6.3 Cooperation. The Parties shall use reasonable efforts to cooperate with each other in the development of their respective Segment of the Project and shall utilize, as appropriate, the measurement tools and protocols established by the Project Managers in accordance with Section 4.3 to monitor implementation. Each Party has selected an appropriate affiliate of ABB as a sole source vendor for its Segment of the Project and intends to enter into a contract with such ABB affiliate for the contemplated Project engineering, design, procurement and/or construction (each, an "ABB Contract"). The Parties agree to simultaneously enter into their respective ABB Contract with the applicable ABB affiliate. Each Party further agrees to coordinate all activities with the ABB affiliate chosen by such Party as necessary for such Party's respective Segment. 6.4 Communications Protocol. 6.4.1 The Project Managers shall meet at such intervals as shall be mutually agreed by the Parties to discuss, among other things, the following: (i) status of schedule and progress for the Project; (ii) status of the approvals by any Governmental Authority; (iii) current and/or emerging problem areas in connection with the Project; and (iv) other relevant information relating to the Project. 6.4.2 A communications protocol satisfactory to each of the Parties shall be developed and distributed by the Project Managers and shall cover those items reasonably necessary to facilitate the Parties' respective consent, input and information rights and obligations contained in this Agreement. 6.5 Good Utility Practice; Compliance 6.5.1 Each Party shall, at all times, perform its obligations under this Agreement in accordance with Good Utility Practice. 6.5.2 Each Party shall, at all times, perform its obligations under this Agreement in accordance with all applicable federal, state and local laws, regulations, rules, ordinances, codes, decrees, judgments, directives, judicial or administrative orders, permits, other duly authorized actions of any Governmental Authority having jurisdiction, ISO requirements, Northeast Power Coordinating Council, Inc. requirements, any other applicable reliability standards and the ISO Open
Access Transmission Tariff ("Applicable Requirements"). To the extent a Party is required or prevented or limited in taking any action by any Applicable Requirement(s), such Party shall not be deemed to be in breach of this Agreement for its compliance therewith. When any Party becomes aware of such a situation, it shall notify the other Party as soon as reasonably practicable. For the avoidance of doubt: neither Party shall be required to undertake or complete any action or performance under this Agreement that is inconsistent with such Party's standard safety practices, its material and equipment specifications, its design criteria and construction procedures, its labor agreements, Good Utility Practice and any Applicable Requirements. ARTICLE 7 PROJECT COSTS 7.1 In General. Except for Shared Costs, each Party shall bear all costs associated with its Segment of the Project, including, without limitation, its in-house labor, materials and any legal costs. 7.2 Shared Costs 7.2.1 The Project Managers may jointly propose that certain specified costs associated with the Project be shared by the Parties. By mutual written agreement, and subject to any required approval of the AOC contemplated by Section 5.10 and/or 7.2(i) of the AOA, the Parties may agree to share such specified costs associated with the Project ("Shared Costs"); any such agreement must specify the methodology and other criteria to be used to allocate the applicable Shared Costs. 7.2.2 With respect to Shared Costs that are costs, fees or expenses payable to unaffiliated third parties, each Party shall use commercially reasonable efforts to cause such third parties to invoice the other Party separately for its allocable share of the Shared Costs to the extent owed by such Party pursuant to Section 7.2.1 of this Agreement. 7.2.3 For the avoidance of doubt: Vermont Electric Transmission Company, New England Hydro-Transmission Corporation, and New England Electric Transmission Corporation shall not be allocated any costs in connection with the Project, whether individually or severally. 7.3 Invoicing. With respect to any Shared Costs that are not invoiced separately pursuant Section 7.2.2, the following procedures shall apply. 7.3.1 Each Party shall bill the other for its allocated share of such Shared Costs by sending a detailed invoice on a quarterly basis (or more frequent if mutually agreed by the Parties from time to time) for approval by the other Party's Project Manager. 7.3.2 The other Party shall have the right to reasonably request additional information concerning any invoice submitted. Within twenty (20) business days of the date of receipt of any invoice, such Party shall promptly pay all amounts in such invoice not reasonably disputed . 7.4 Interest. Interest shall accrue at the Federal Funds Rate (as in effect from time to time) on overdue Shared Costs amounts not reasonably disputed and, such interest, together with such overdue amounts, shall be immediately due and payable. Interest on disputed amounts later determined to be due shall accrue at such rate for the period specified in Section 7.5 of this Agreement. 7.5 Billing Disputes. In the event that either Party ("Disputing Party"), in good faith, disputes any amount charged to it, the Disputing Party shall state in writing the reason for such dispute in reasonable detail not later than the due date of the invoice containing such disputed amount, whereupon the other Party ("Billing Party") shall provide the Disputing Party with a written explanation concerning the amount in dispute. If the Project Parties agree that the amount billed is incorrect, the correction shall be reflected in the next invoice as a debit or a credit, as applicable. If any disputed amounts are later determined to have been due at the time of invoice, such amounts shall be considered overdue from twenty (20) business days after invoice until repaid in full with interest for the purpose of calculating interest pursuant to Section 7.4 of this Agreement and, together with such interest, shall be immediately due and payable upon such determination. 7.6 Audits. During the term of this Agreement and for three (3) years thereafter, upon reasonable prior written notice (which shall in no event be less than ten (10) business days) and during normal business hours, each Party ("Auditing Party") shall have the right to perform an audit of the Shared Costs paid by either Party. Each Party (as the "Audited Party") agrees that it shall make available at its offices for review such of its books and records that relate to the Shared Costs as are reasonably requested by the Auditing Party. 7.7 Costs of Audits; Adjustments. The cost of such audits shall be paid by the Auditing Party; provided, however, that if the audit reveals that the Auditing Party has overpaid by five percent (5%) or more of the Shared Costs being audited, the Audited Party shall pay the costs of the audit. If, following any such audit, it is determined that any Party was undercharged or overcharged with respect to the Shared Costs being audited, all payments or refunds necessary to rectify such overcharge or undercharge shall be made within a reasonable time (but in no event longer than ninety (90) days) from delivery of the audit findings) by the responsible Party. 7.8 Final Accounting. Within six (6) months after the date by which Substantial Completion (as such term is defined in the applicable Party's ABB Contract) has occurred under both ABB Contracts, a final accounting of Shared Costs shall be completed by each Party and delivered to the other Party. If a Party has borne less than its allocated share of Shared Costs (as determined in accordance with the allocation methodology specified in the applicable written agreement(s) referred to in Section 7.2.1), such Party shall make a true-up payment to the other Party to correct such underpayment, such true-up payment shall be without interest (except as interest is otherwise due and owing under the other provisions of this Agreement) and shall be made within twenty (20) business days after determination that such underpayment occurred. ARTICLE 8 APPLICABILITY OF THE ASSET OWNER AGREEMENT 8.1 The Project consists of upgrades within the meaning of Sections 5.10 and 7.2 (i) of the AOA. This Agreement shall be subject to the terms and conditions of the AOA including, without limitation, Articles VIII (Confidentiality), IX (Force Majeure), XI (Indemnification; Insurance; Limitations on Liability)), XII (Applicable Law) and XIII (Dispute Resolution). ARTICLE 9 MISCELLANEOUS 9.1 Default; Termination. 9.1.1 For the avoidance of doubt: neither Party shall have a right to terminate this Agreement for convenience. 9.1.2 A Party shall be considered in breach of this Agreement, if such Party (the "Breaching Party") shall fail in any material respect to comply with, observe or perform, or default in the performance of, any other material covenant or obligation under this Agreement (a "Breach"). A Breach of this Agreement shall become an "Event of Default" if, after receipt of written notice from the non-Breaching Party, such Breach continues for a period of thirty (30) days after such notice, provided, however, such thirty (30) day cure period shall be extended for a further reasonable period if the Breach could not reasonably be cured within the initial thirty (30) day cure period (but only if the Breaching Party is, at all times, diligently pursuing such cure.) Upon the occurrence of an Event of Default, the Parties agree to continue performance under this Agreement, provided, that, the non-Breaching Party shall be entitled to exercise all rights and remedies (other than any right to terminate or suspend performance hereunder) arising from such Event of Default. 9.1.3. For clarity, the overall testing done by HQ Transnergie at its IREQ institute and the installation by HQ Transnergie at Nicolet Converter Station will benefit the whole Project and may cause the Parties to mutually revise, adjust and refine the Project schedule ("Adjustments"). The Parties agree that such Adjustments, by either Party, shall not be a Breach or an Event of Default and they agree to each assume its own related costs with respect to such Adjustments. 9.2 Conflicts. To the extent that any provision of this Agreement conflicts with the terms and conditions of the AOA, the provisions of the AOA shall govern. 9.3 Binding Effect. This Agreement and the rights and obligations hereof, shall be binding upon, and shall inure to the benefit of, the successors and permitted assigns of the Parties hereto. 9.4 Required Authorizations. This Agreement and all rights, obligations, and performances of the Parties hereunder are subject to all applicable federal and state laws and to all duly promulgated orders and other duly authorized action of Governmental Authorities having jurisdiction (each, a "Required Authorization"). If and to the extent the performance of any obligation by a Party hereunder requires the prior authorization of a Governmental Authority or of any other third party (including, without limitation, the issuance or acquisition of any approval, order, permit, consent, waiver, license, certificate or release) such Party's obligation to perform shall be subject to the prior receipt of all such authorizations in form and substance satisfactory to the Party needing such authorizations. On June 18, 2013, the Conseil du Trsor has approved the request of HQ Transnergie to enter into a contract with ABB inc., understanding that the permission does not absolve ABB inc. to complete the steps required to obtain from the Autorit des marchs financiers (AMF) the authorization to contract, as quickly as possible. In case of refusal of the AMF, HQ Transnergie will not have a Required Authorization contemplated herein. National Grid shall file this Agreement with the FERC promptly following its execution by both Parties. If this Agreement is not accepted or approved by the FERC, National Grid will not have a Required Authorization contemplated herein. 9.5 Severability. In the event that any portion or part of this Agreement is held to be illegal or unenforceable to any extent, the legality, validity and enforceability of the remainder of this Agreement shall not be affected thereby, and shall remain in full force and effect and shall be enforced to the greatest extent permitted by applicable law. 9.6 This Agreement shall be binding upon and inure solely to the benefit of each Party hereto, as well as their successors and permitted assigns, and nothing in this Agreement, express or implied, is intended to or shall confer upon any other person or entity any right, benefit or remedy of any nature whatsoever under or by reason of this Agreement.
9.7 Headings, Captions, References. The headings, as well as Article and Section captions, in this Agreement are included for convenience of reference only and shall not constitute a part of this Agreement for any other purpose, or limit or be used as an aid in construing the provisions of this Agreement. 9.8 Entire Agreement. This Agreement and the AOA, including all appendices, attachments and exhibits attached hereto or thereto, constitute the entire agreement between the Parties with reference to the subject matter hereof, and supersede all prior and contemporaneous understandings or agreements, oral or written, between the Parties with respect to the subject matter of this Agreement. There are no other agreements, representations, warranties, or covenants which constitute any part of the consideration for, or any condition to, any Party's compliance with its obligations under this Agreement. 9.9 Notices. Any notice or other communication with respect to this Agreement shall be made in writing and shall be considered as having been given if delivered in person, by nationally recognized overnight courier, by facsimile, by e-mail or by certified mail (return receipt requested) to: If to National Grid: National Grid Attention: Glenn Lyford, Project Manager 40 Sylvan Road Waltham, MA 02451 (781) 522-1068 glen.lyford@nationalgrid.com If to HQ Transnergie: Hydro-Qubec Transnergie a/s: Patrick Zanchette, Project Manager, MTDCN Control and Protection Replacement Complexe Desjardins Montral (Qubec) H5B 1H7 - tage 9 Zanchette.Patrick@hydro.qc.ca 9.10 Safety. Each Party shall be solely responsible for the safety and supervision of its own employees, representatives, and subcontractors involved with such Party's work or any other activities contemplated by this Agreement. In connection with the performance contemplated by this Agreement, each Party shall, and shall require its representatives, contractors, subcontractors, and employees to, comply with all applicable Federal, state, and local health and safety requirements, rules, regulations, laws, and ordinances. 9.11 No Joint Venture. The Parties shall at all times be independent contractors and not agents, employees, partners or joint venturers of each other. No Party shall have any right, power or authority to enter into any agreement or undertaking for, or act on behalf of, or to act as or be an agent or representative of, or to otherwise bind, the other Party. The liability of each Party in connection with this Agreement shall be several and not joint. 9.12 Subcontracting; Assignment. Each Party has the right to subcontract some or all of the work to be performed by such Party under the terms of this Agreement. Each Party may also use the services of its Affiliates in connection with its performance under this Agreement. This Agreement may not be assigned by any Party without the prior written consent of all of the other Parties, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed. The foregoing notwithstanding, any Party may assign this Agreement to an Affiliate of such Party. For purposes of this section, (i) an "Affiliate" of a Party shall mean any entity controlling, controlled by or under common control with such Party and (ii) "control" of an entity shall mean the ownership, with right to vote, of fifty percent (50%) or more of the outstanding voting securities, equity, membership interests, or equivalent of such entity. 9.13 Exercise of Right; Waivers; Amendments. No failure or delay on the part of any Party in exercising any right, power, or privilege hereunder, and no course of dealing between the Parties, shall operate as a waiver thereof; nor shall any single or partial exercise of any right, power, or privilege hereunder preclude any other or further exercise thereof or the exercise of any other right, power, or privilege. This Agreement may not be amended or modified in any way, and none of its provisions may be waived, except by a writing signed by an authorized representative of each Party. The Project Managers shall not be authorized representatives within the meaning of this Section. 9.14 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in multiple counterparts, each of which shall be considered an original instrument, but all of which shall be considered one and the same Agreement, and shall become binding when all counterparts have been signed by each of the Parties and delivered to each Party hereto. Delivery of an executed signature page counterpart by email shall be as effective as delivery of a manually executed counterpart. [The remainder of this page is intentionally left blank. AMENDED AND RESTATED PHASE II MASSACHUSETTS TRANSMISSION FACILITIES SUPPORT AGREEMENT This Amended and Restated Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement (the "Agreement"), dated as of November 1, 2020 and effective as of January 1, 2021 (the "Effective Date"), subject to the conditions precedent specified in Section 3 herein being met, is between New England Hydro-Transmission Electric Company, Inc. ("New England Hydro") and the signatories listed in Attachment A to this Agreement (the signatories listed in Attachment A and meeting the further conditions for participation hereunder are hereinafter referred to as "Participants" or individually as a "Participant" but their rights and obligations hereunder are several and not joint as described in Section 6 hereof; New England Hydro and the Participants are referred to herein as the "Parties" or "Party"). This Agreement amends and restates the Initial Agreement (defined below). Recitals WHEREAS, the Parties were parties to the original Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, which was initially entered into on June 1, 1985, with amendments dated May 1, 1986, February 1, 1987, June 1, 1987, September 1, 1987, October 1, 1987, August 1, 1988, and January 1, 1989 (the "Initial Agreement"). WHEREAS, the Initial Agreement provides for an initial term that expires as of October 31, 2020; WHEREAS, the Initial Agreement also provides an option to the Participants to extend the Initial Agreement upon the same terms and conditions therein for up to an additional twenty years under certain conditions specified therein; WHEREAS, those conditions being met, the Participants have exercised their right to extend the Initial Agreement for an additional twenty year term and wish to make revisions to the Initial Agreement appropriate for such extension; WHEREAS, this Agreement is an integral part of a set of interrelated contracts referred to herein as the Basic Agreements that set forth the rights and obligations regarding the Interconnection; WHEREAS, the fundamental purposes of the Basic Agreements including this Agreement, are to provide for; (a) secure financial support for the costs of the Interconnection, and appropriate investment return for the owners of the assets; and (b) certain benefits to the IRH in return for their financial support for the Interconnection, including but not limited to: (i) transmission rights to the transmission transfer capability on the Interconnection between New England and Quebec up to the maximum transfer capability of 2,000 MW in accordance with Good Utility Practice; (ii) the ability to import and export energy, capacity, and ancillary services between the ISO-NE and Hydro-Quebec transmission systems for commercial and reliability purposes, promoting economic and environmental benefits to customers in New England by facilitating the delivery of zero-carbon energy at a reasonable cost; and (iii) an operable Interconnection to allow for use of the Use Rights and to promote reliability and energy security related benefits to New England; and WHEREAS, the Parties desire to amend and restate the Agreement, as amended and restated herein, effective as of January 1, 2021; NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises, the execution of the other Basic Agreements hereinafter referred to, the mutual covenants hereinafter and therein set forth, and other good and valuable consideration, receipt of which is hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows: Section 1: Definitions The capitalized terms below shall have the following meanings: Advisory Committee: shall mean the Interconnection Rights Holders ("IRH") Management Committee, as provided for under the Use Agreement. Basic Agreements: shall mean the following agreements: the Support Agreements, the Equity Funding Agreements and the Use Agreement. Entitlement Transaction: shall mean any transaction utilizing the Interconnection allowed under the Use Agreement other than an Emergency Energy transaction. Equity Funding Agreements: shall mean: (1) the Equity Funding Agreement for New England Hydro-Transmission Electric Company, Inc., dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated May 1, 1986, September 1, 1987, and August 1, 1988, as it may be subsequently amended; and (2) the Equity Funding Agreement for New England Hydro-Transmission Corporation, dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated May 1, 1986, September 1, 1987, and August 1, 1988, as it may be subsequently amended. FERC: shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. Good Utility Practice: shall mean any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather includes all acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the New England region. Governmental Authority or Governmental Authorities: shall mean any executive, legislative, judicial, regulatory or administrative agency, body, commission, department, board, court, tribunal, arbitrating body or authority of the United States or any foreign country, or any state, local or other governmental subdivision thereof. Initial Agreement: shall have the meaning set forth in the recitals. Interconnection: shall mean the high-voltage, direct current ("HVDC") interconnection, transmission and converter terminal facilities in the United States interconnecting the Hydro-Quebec system and the ISO-NE system, provided for and described in the Basic Agreements, with a nominal transfer capability of 2,000 megawatts ("MW"). Interconnection Rights Holders ("IRH"): shall mean the parties to the Support Agreements that have the financial obligation to pay for the costs of the Interconnection in exchange for the Use Rights granted under the Support Agreements. Section 2: Basic Understandings Together with this Agreement for Phase II, some or all of the Participants are also participants in the Phase I Support Agreements and the Amended and Restated Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement. Phase I of the Interconnection consists of the United States portion of a 450 kV HVDC transmission line from a terminal at the Des Cantons Substation on the Hydro-Quebec system near Sherbrooke, Quebec to the location of the former terminal having had a Nominal rating of 690 MW which was adjacent to a substation at the location of the Comerford Generating Station on the Connecticut River (hereinafter referred to as Phase I). In 2012, the Phase I Terminal Facilities were retired and the substation interconnection was decommissioned, leaving the remaining Phase I HVDC facilities and equipment to be utilized solely with Phase II. The facilities covered under the Phase I and Phase II Support Agreements are integrally related and interdependent facilities, and the Parties intend that they be treated accordingly under the Basic Agreements. The Basic Agreements are intended to work together as a set of interrelated agreements governing participation in the Interconnection and the rights and obligations that result from such participation. The portion of Phase II in the United States consists of an extension of the Phase I HVDC transmission line from Phase I at the Comerford Generating Station location through New Hampshire to Sandy Pond in Massachusetts with additional Terminal Facilities installed at Sandy Pond that increased the prior transfer capacity from Hydro-Quebec to approximately 2,000 MW, where conditions permit in accordance with Good Utility Practice. The Parties have made commitments under the Basic Agreements to obtain the benefits of the Interconnection, as further described in the recitals above. In connection with the benefits intended under the Basic Agreements, the Parties also recognize certain other agreements and tariff provisions are important to the intended benefits under the Basic Agreements. These other agreements include: (i) a certain Asset Owners Agreement between the asset owners of Interconnection facilities and the asset owners of the interconnected facilities in Quebec; (ii) the Interconnection Operators Agreement between the system operators in the United States and Quebec; (iii) the Phase II Maine Electric Power SVC Support Agreement between New England Hydro-Transmission Corp. and Maine Electric Power Company to provide for certain static var compensator facilities specified in that agreement important to the reliable operation of the Interconnection; (iv) the Transmission Service Administration Agreement among the IMC, ISO-NE and certain individual IRH (known as the Schedule 20A Service Providers) to provide for administration of transmission service over the Interconnection; (v) the HVDC Transmission Operating Agreement among the Asset Owners and ISO-NE; (vi) certain agreements related to the improvements and reinforcements to AC transmission systems in Massachusetts necessitated by Phase II, and referred to as the "Phase II New England Power AC Facilities Support Agreement" and the "Phase II Boston Edison AC Facilities Support Agreement"; and (vii) the provisions of the ISO-NE tariff and any successor provisions that provide for HQ Interconnection Capability Credits (as defined in that tariff) or similar benefits. The Parties agree to act toward these other agreements and tariff provisions in such a way as to promote the intended benefits under the Basic Agreements. Transmission services over Phase II shall be on terms and conditions provided for in this Agreement, agreed upon among the Participants in the Use Agreement, and as otherwise provided for under the requirements of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and applicable rate schedules and transmission tariffs. Each Participant represents that it made its own independent investigations and inquiries into the projected costs and benefits of this Agreement as it deemed appropriate and did not rely upon representations (other than those contained in this Agreement) of New England Hydro or its affiliates in deciding to enter into this Agreement. Each Participant acknowledges that the benefits of participating in Phase II described in this Agreement and in the Use Agreement are the fundamental considerations for its signing of this Agreement and making the significant commitments to each other Participant specified herein and to the participants in the other Support Agreements. Section 4: Effective Date and Term This Agreement shall become effective upon the Effective Date, as provided for in Section 3 of this Agreement. This Agreement shall expire on October 31, 2040; provided, however, that if the Transmission Facilities are operational and, at the time of such election, there are commitments to support the full costs of the Transmission Facilities for the full renewal term, a Participant shall be entitled to elect to continue participation for an additional period of up to 20 years upon the terms and conditions of this Agreement (with any amendments mutually agreed to by the Parties). Each Participant must provide notice in writing of its election to continue participation no later than by July 1, 2035 to the Advisory Committee. The Advisory Committee shall determine the length of any such extended term by August 1, 2035. The Advisory Committee must provide notice in writing no later than by November 1, 2035, to New England Hydro of the Participant elections to continue participation and the length of such extended term. Notification will be given to each Participant by New England Hydro of such option to continue participation by no later than May 1, 2035. New England Hydro shall determine, in its sole discretion, whether the Participants electing to continue participation reasonably can be anticipated to support the full cost of the Transmission Facilities during the proposed extended term and shall inform each electing Participant of that determination no later than November 1, 2038. In order to inform such determination, the Participants seeking to renew shall, upon request, provide documentation that New England Hydro may require in its discretion addressing the ability of those Participants to support the full costs of the Transmission Facilities over the proposed additional term, including but not limited to representations from all Participants and credit support from any Participants seeking to renew that are not "investment grade" Participants. It is anticipated by the Participants and New England Hydro that during the period November 1, 2035 through November 1, 2038, New England Hydro and the Participants electing to continue participation shall work collectively and in good faith to assist New England Hydro in its determination. As of November 1, 2038, if the determination of New England Hydro, in its sole discretion, is that the Participants electing to continue participation cannot support the full costs of the Transmission Facilities, New England Hydro shall so notify all Participants stating the reasons for such determination. As a result of such determination, New England Hydro shall be free to take any action it deems appropriate including, but not limited to termination of the Agreement as of November 1, 2040, in accordance with Section 16, restructuring of the Agreement, continuing operation of the Transmission Facilities under alternative cost recovery provisions to be approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, sale of the Transmission Facilities or any other action it deems appropriate in light of the circumstances and facts known at the time of such determination and shall notify all Participants of such proposed action on November 1, 2038. Each Participant which is also a participant under the Phase I Support Agreements or the Amended and Restated Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement shall exercise its rights and take all actions under the Phase I Support Agreements or the Amended and Restated Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement to assure that the Phase I facilities and the New Hampshire Phase II facilities are available to permit continued operation of Phase II for the full term of this Agreement; provided that the foregoing provision shall in no way limit the Advisory Committee's rights to act under this Agreement. Section 7: Advisory Committee The IRH Management Committee, as provided for under the Use Agreement and acting in accordance with the governance provisions of the Use Agreement, shall be the Advisory Committee and shall approve the by-laws of the Advisory Committee. Membership in and governance of the Advisory Committee shall be in accordance with the Use Agreement. The Advisory Committee shall have the power and responsibilities set forth in this Agreement and the Use Agreement and shall adopt its own by-laws, provided that (i) voting shall be by Participating Shares at the time of the vote, (ii) a vote of two-thirds or more of Participating Shares is required to accept a New England Hydro proposal or to take other affirmative action and a vote of more than one-third is required to reject a New England Hydro proposal, and (iii) one or more Participants having Participating Shares of at least 10% in the aggregate may by reasonable written notice to all Participants call a meeting of the Advisory Committee. The Advisory Committee shall advise New England Hydro on all major matters of concern to the Participants regarding the Transmission Facilities and the Interconnection. New England Hydro shall make prompt proposals for decisions on the following, and shall not act without approval from the Advisory Committee unless it reasonably believes that failure to act would be inconsistent with Good Utility Practice or the intent of this Agreement and provides such opinion to the Advisory Committee in writing. In addition to the general responsibilities and authority of the Advisory Committee, the Advisory Committee shall accept or reject proposals for decisions on the following specific items: (i) Overall project budget estimate for design, engineering and construction of upgrades to the Transmission Facilities whose costs would be in excess of $5 million; (ii) Major changes to the original design concept of upgrades to the Transmission Facilities that, based on reasonable engineering estimates, will increase or decrease the cost of upgrades by more than 10% of the overall budget approved in (i) above or might have a significant detrimental effect on reliability or availability of the Transmission Facilities; (iii) General terms of major contracts in excess of $25 million; (iv) Capital additions to the Transmission Facilities in excess of $5 million; (v) Major changes in operation and maintenance of the Transmission Facilities that will increase operation and maintenance costs by more than 10% of the previous year's actual operation and maintenance costs or might have a significant detrimental effect on the Use Rights or on the reliability, operability or use of the Transmission Facilities; (vi) Delay, restriction, suspension, termination or cancellation of planning or construction, or shut down of the Transmission Facilities, for a period of six months or longer or permanently under Section 16; (vii) The term of any New England Hydro debt financing or any other financial arrangements (other than any construction financing) with a principal amount in excess of $25 million, provided that such term must be between 5 and 30 years; and (viii) Such other matters as are specified elsewhere in this Agreement. If New England Hydro makes a proposal for a decision from the Advisory Committee and the Advisory Committee fails, however, to accept or reject such proposal within the later of: (i) 45 days of New England Hydro providing the Advisory Committee with information that reasonably describes the proposal and attempts to answer questions from the Participants, or (ii) a period 45 days after New England Hydro has provided any additional information requested by the Advisory Committee, provided that in no instance shall such total period be longer than 90 days after New England Hydro provides the Advisory Committee with notice of its proposal, the Advisory Committee shall be deemed by New England Hydro to have approved New England Hydro's proposal and New England Hydro may immediately proceed to implement its proposal. Section 8: Design and Construction of Upgrades to the Transmission Facilities
Except for those areas of responsibility assigned to the Advisory Committee as specified in Section 7, New England Hydro shall be responsible for the design, engineering, procurement, installation, and all other aspects of the construction of upgrades to the Transmission Facilities, all in accordance with Good Utility Practice for the benefit of all Participants, the objective being to achieve an appropriate balance among minimization of construction cost, minimization of operation and maintenance cost, licensing and environmental considerations, and safety and reliability of service. In carrying out these activities, New England Hydro may utilize the services of its affiliates and may also select and employ a financial adviser, legal counsel, design engineering firm, a construction engineering firm, consultants, and such other firms as it considers desirable. To the extent services are performed by an affiliate of New England Hydro, such affiliate will charge on the same basis that it would charge its costs to other affiliates in accordance with applicable laws and regulations. In its design and construction of any upgrades to the Transmission Facilities, New England Hydro shall, consistent with Good Utility Practice, coordinate as appropriate with the other owners of the Interconnection facilities and with the owner and operator of transmission facilities interconnected to the Interconnection on the Quebec side of the border. In order for the Advisory Committee to meet its responsibilities as specified in Section 7, New England Hydro shall provide all necessary information reasonably requested by the Advisory Committee. During the course of such work, New England Hydro shall furnish reports, either quarterly or monthly in New England Hydro's sole discretion, to the Advisory Committee with respect to the progress of the work and an annual report to the Advisory Committee of actual and estimated construction expenditures for the Transmission Facilities. Section 9: Operation and Maintenance of the Transmission Facilities Except for those areas of responsibility assigned to the Advisory Committee as specified in Section 7, New England Hydro shall be responsible for the operation and maintenance of the Transmission Facilities in accordance with Good Utility Practice for the benefit of all Participants, the objective being to operate the Transmission Facilities as efficiently, economically, safely, and reliably as feasible. New England Hydro shall use its best efforts to coordinate the operation and maintenance of the Transmission Facilities with the operation and maintenance of the Phase I facilities and other Phase II facilities. New England Hydro shall operate and maintain the Transmission Facilities in accordance with applicable reliability criteria. In carrying out these activities, New England Hydro may utilize the services of its affiliates and may also select and employ a financial adviser, legal counsel, consultants, and such other firms as it considers desirable. In furtherance of its responsibility, New England Hydro may from time to time designate a company, which need not be a Participant, to operate and maintain the Transmission Facilities. To the extent services are performed by an affiliate of New England Hydro, such affiliate will charge its costs on the same basis that it would charge to other affiliates pursuant to applicable laws and regulations. In its operation and maintenance of any upgrades to the Transmission Facilities, New England Hydro shall, consistent with Good Utility Practice, coordinate as appropriate with the other owners of the Interconnection facilities and with the owner and operator of transmission facilities interconnected to the Interconnection on the Quebec side of the border. In order for the Advisory Committee to meet its responsibilities as specified in Section 7, New England Hydro shall provide all necessary information reasonably requested by the Advisory Committee. For the duration of this Agreement, New England Hydro shall furnish bi-monthly reports to the Advisory Committee with respect to the availability, operation and maintenance of the Transmission Facilities and an annual report to the Advisory Committee of estimated operation and maintenance expenses and projected capital expenditures. Any amount provided as an estimate represents New England Hydro's preliminary cost estimates, which are subject to adjustment and alteration, and do not constitute any binding commitment. New England Hydro shall have no liability arising from any change in the cost estimate(s) provided hereunder. Section 10: New England Hydro Relationship to Participants In carrying out its responsibilities hereunder, New England Hydro agrees that it shall use its best efforts to act for the collective benefit of all Participants and New England Hydro, to include in its contracts with independent contractors the customary provisions for assuring professional and workmanlike performance, including warranties, insurance coverage and other protections consistent with Good Utility Practice, and to enforce its rights under such contracts against the other contracting parties to the extent reasonable, reserving the discretion to settle claims on a reasonable basis. All costs of construction, including damages caused by the risks of negligence (other than gross negligence) and other risks of construction in excess of the recoveries obtained from offending parties or insurers, shall be included as part of "Investment in the Transmission Facilities" (as defined in Section 12 below) and all costs of operating the Transmission Facilities, including damages caused by risks of negligence (other than gross negligence) or other risks of operation in excess of any recoveries obtained from offending parties or insurers, shall be included in New England Hydro's "Operating Expenses" (as defined in Section 12 below). Section 11: Transmission and Other Services In accordance with Good Utility Practice, New England Hydro shall perform its obligations under this Agreement so as to enable the Parties to obtain the benefits intended under the Basic Agreements, as described in the recitals to this Agreement. In exchange for each Participant's ongoing commitment to support the costs of the Transmission Facilities, New England Hydro hereby grants to each Participant an exclusive right to use its Participating Share of the Transmission Facilities in accordance with the Use Agreement and applicable requirements of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and applicable rate schedules and transmission tariffs. New England Hydro agrees that it will serve as an agent or in other similar capacity for any Participant that so requests for the buying or selling of power to be transmitted over the Transmission Facilities as an Entitlement Transaction pursuant to the terms of the Use Agreement or otherwise, provided, however, that a formal written contract with terms and conditions, including compensation for services, satisfactory to New England Hydro is executed and delivered prior to performance of such services. Section 12: Support Charge Commencing in the month of the Effective Date and in each month thereafter, each Participant shall pay in accordance with Section 13 its Participating Share of a monthly Support Charge in an amount determined in accordance with this Section 12. In the event that: (1) any Participant becomes a Credit Enhanced Participant after the Effective Date, and (2) New England Hydro determines in its sole discretion that credit support is needed to finance one or more upgrades to the Transmission Facilities, each Participant shall pay in accordance with Section 13 its Participating Share of a Credit Enhancement Charge defined and calculated in accordance with Attachment D. The Support Charge shall be equal to New England Hydro's Total Cost of Service Related to the Transmission Facilities for such month. The "Total Cost of Service Related to the Transmission Facilities" for any month commencing with the month in which the Effective Date occurs shall be the sum of (a) New England Hydro's Operating Expenses for such month with respect to the Transmission Facilities, plus (b) an amount equal to one-twelfth of the Composite Percentage for such month times the Average Net Rate Base for the Transmission Facilities, less (c) investment earnings of the Debt Service Fund, as defined in Section 18, realized by New England Hydro, less (d) any other income received by New England Hydro resulting from costs or rate base supported by the Participants other than income received pursuant to (a), (b), or (c) above or Credit Enhancement Charges and other income allocated to Equity Sponsors elsewhere under this Agreement. If a Support Charge payment under Section 13 is to be calculated from a date other than the first day of a month, an appropriate proration of the amount determined in (b) above shall be made for such payment only. "Uniform System" shall mean the appropriate Uniform System of Accounts prescribed by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) for Public Utilities and Licensees, as from time to time in effect. New England Hydro's "Operating Expenses" shall include all amounts related to the Transmission Facilities and properly chargeable to expense accounts less any applicable credits thereto, in accordance with the Uniform System, including but not limited to operation and maintenance expense such as rent on leased property and administrative and general expenses, state and Federal income and franchise taxes, property taxes, payroll taxes, any other taxes not based on income, and depreciation and/or amortization expense; it being understood that rents on leased property shall include the rental of property or property rights related to the Transmission Facilities from any Participant with rent based on book value. In addition, each Participant will pay to New England Hydro, and New England Hydro will pay to New England Power Company, for the benefit of its customers, such Participant's Participating Share of a monthly charge of $49,000 to compensate New England Power for the lost capacity on its Massachusetts right-of-way, provided however that no such charge shall be paid during such time as construction or operation is suspended on account of a defect in title for such rights-of-way. The allowance for state and Federal income taxes included in Operating Expenses shall reflect the normalization of timing differences, the flow through of permanent differences between book income and tax income, and amortization of excess or deficient deferred income taxes as a result of changes to federal, state or local tax rates as recorded in FERC account 411.1 or 410.1 and including tax gross up as calculated in this Attachment F. New England Hydro, as the tax owner of the Transmission Facilities, will be entitled to the benefits and subject to the burdens of such ownership for tax purposes. The allowance for state and Federal income taxes included in Operating Expenses shall include a provision for taxes on dividends received by stockholders, calculated at the then current statutory rate for corporate stockholders. The "Investment in the Transmission Facilities" shall be the aggregate amount incurred at any time either before or after commercial operation of the Transmission Facilities which relates to the Transmission Facilities and is properly chargeable to New England Hydro's utility plant accounts in accordance with the Uniform System. The Investment in the Transmission Facilities shall also include: (1) Operating Expenses incurred prior to the date of commercial operation of the Transmission Facilities, Operating Expenses incurred prior to the date of commercial operation of any upgrades to the Transmission Facilities to the extent consistent with the Uniform System or otherwise approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, and (2) an allowance for funds used during the period prior to the date of commercial operation of the Transmission Facilities, or the date of commercial operation of any upgrades to the Transmission Facilities to the extent consistent with the Uniform System or otherwise approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, (AFDC) accrued on the Investment in the Transmission Facilities. The AFDC rate shall be calculated pursuant to the last FERC approved AFDC formula including in construction work in progress all Investment in the Transmission Facilities prior to the date the Transmission Facilities or upgrades to the Transmission Facilities are placed in commercial operation and using 11.07% as the Return on Equity for such calculation. "Composite Percentage" shall be computed as of the last day of each month (the "Computation Date"). "Composite Percentage" as of a Computation Date shall be the sum of (i) Return on Equity then in effect multiplied by the percentage which Equity Investment as of such date is of the Total Capital as of such date; plus (ii) the average monthly effective interest rate per annum of each principal amount of indebtedness outstanding on such date for money borrowed, whether long term or short term, multiplied by the percentage which each such principal amount is of Total Capital as of such date. The effective interest rate shall take into account premiums, discounts, fees, and other costs that are related to the indebtedness. "Return on Equity" shall be 11.07%. "Equity Investment" as of any date shall consist of the sum of (i) all amounts theretofore paid to New England Hydro for all capital stock theretofore issued, plus all capital contributions, less the sum of any amounts paid by New England Hydro in the form of stock retirements, repurchases or redemptions or return of capital including liquidating dividends; plus (ii) any credit balance in the capital surplus account not included in (i) and any credit balance in the earned surplus (retained earnings) account on the books of New England Hydro as of such date. "Total Capital" as of any date shall be calculated based on the capital structure used to determine Support Charges in accordance with this Section 12. From the Effective Date until the first to occur of June 30 or December 31 thereafter, the "Average Net Rate Base" for the Transmission Facilities shall be the average of the net rate base determined as of the Effective Date and the first to occur of June 30 or December 31 thereafter. Thereafter, for subsequent months of January through June, Average Net Rate Base shall be the average of the Net Rate Base as of the preceding December 31 and the following June 30. For other months, Average Net Rate Base shall be the average of the Net Rate Base as of the preceding June 30 and the following December 31. The "Net Rate Base" shall consist of (i) the Investment in the Transmission Facilities, less (ii) the amount of any accumulated provision for depreciation and amortization related to the Investment in the Transmission Facilities, less (or plus) (iii) the amount of any reserve for deferred income taxes received (or paid) by New England Hydro, such deferred income taxes to include deferred income taxes due to accelerated depreciation, construction tax benefits, and any other book/tax timing differences related to the Transmission Facilities, less (iv) the amount of any unamortized investment tax credits (ITC), less (or plus) (v) regulatory liabilities or assets associated with excess or deficient deferred income taxes as a result of changes in federal, state or local tax rates and other rate changes as recorded in FERC account 182.3 or FERC account 254 and including tax gross up as calculated in this Attachment F, , plus (vi) such allowances related to the Transmission Facilities for materials and supplies, prepaid items and cash working capital as may from time to time be determined by New England Hydro, as reasonably necessary and in accordance with accepted utility accounting practice, plus (vi) the amounts held in the Debt Service Fund, as described in Section 18. New England Hydro shall normalize ITC over the depreciation and/or amortization period relating to the Transmission Facilities. Any allowance for cash working capital shall be limited to that not sufficiently recovered through the use of estimated billing for the current month. The costs of the Advisory Committee shall be treated as a Support Charge and paid for by the Participants in accordance with the Support Charge and payment provisions of this Agreement and the other Support Agreements. Any capital upgrades to the Transmission Facilities placed in service on or after September 2020 shall be depreciated on a straight-line basis over the remaining book life of the assets in accordance with the depreciation rates set forth in Attachment E. By no later than five years from the Commission-approved Effective Date, New England Hydro shall prepare updated depreciation studies and shall present the results of such studies to the Advisory Committee. Based on the results of those depreciation studies, New England Hydro shall engage in good faith discussions with the Advisory Committee as to the appropriateness of New England Hydro submitting a filing to FERC under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act to update the depreciation rates set forth in Attachment E. By no later than five years after the presentation of the most recent depreciation studies to the Advisory Committee, New England Hydro shall request that the Advisory Committee determine, through a vote in accordance with Section 7, whether New England Hydro shall prepare additional updated depreciation studies. If the Advisory Committee so determines, New England Hydro shall present the results of those depreciation studies to the Advisory Committee and engage in good faith discussions with the Advisory Committee as to the appropriateness of New England Hydro submitting a filing to FERC under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act to update the depreciation rates set forth in Attachment E. Any future changes to depreciation and/or amortization rates to be submitted for acceptance by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission shall be at a rate sufficient to recover the Investment in the Transmission Facilities (including estimated cost of removal less any salvage value which salvage value, for the purpose of calculating such depreciation and/or amortization, will not exceed the amount of cost of removal), regardless of when the upgrades are built and placed in service. In accordance with Section 4, by November 1, 2035, the Advisory Committee shall provide notice to New England Hydro of all Participants which intend to renew participation in this Agreement for an additional renewal term of up to 20 years, as determined by the Advisory Committee no later than August 1, 2035. If the notice from the Advisory Committee does not state that a total number of Participants responsible for at least 75% of the cost responsibility for Support Charges under this Agreement intend to renew participation for the full renewal term, New England Hydro will engage in reasonable efforts to develop and obtain FERC approval of alternative cost recovery arrangements for any portion of the Transmission Facilities that will not be fully depreciated by October 31, 2040. If FERC fails to approve such alternative cost recovery arrangements, or if FERC conditions such alternative cost recovery arrangements in a manner unacceptable to New England Hydro, then the depreciation and/or amortization shall be modified at a rate sufficient to recover all Investment in the Transmission Facilities (including estimated cost of removal less any salvage value which salvage value, for the purpose of calculating such depreciation and/or amortization, will not exceed the amount of cost of removal) by October 31, 2040. The capital structure used to determine Support Charges will remain at 100% equity financing until the total Average Net Rate Base for the Transmission Facilities that are the subject of this Agreement along with the transmission facilities that are the subject of the Amended and Restated Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement and the transmission facilities that are the subject of the Amended and Restated Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Line Support Agreement meets or exceeds $25 million. At that time, the Support Charges will be based on a hypothetical capital structure of 65% equity and 35% debt. The provisions establishing an 11.07% Return on Equity and addressing capital structure in the preceding paragraphs as well as the depreciation rates set forth in Attachment E shall be subject to a moratorium on any changes made or proposed by any Party under Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act. The moratorium period shall commence on the filing date of Agreement with the Commission and shall end five years from the Commission-approved Effective Date. During this moratorium, no Party may propose any increase or decrease to the 11.07% Return on Equity under Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act including through any Return on Equity incentive adder or through any adjustment to the Return on Equity as a result of a change in the Commission's Return on Equity policies. Section 13: Payments Commencing on or about the Effective Date and for each month thereafter, New England Hydro shall render to each Participant an invoice for its Participating Share of the Support Charge and the Credit Enhancement Charge, if any, for such month calculated on a one-month lag using actual results for such month. Unless New England Hydro is prevented by circumstances beyond its reasonable control, New England Hydro shall use its best efforts to render final bills within two years after the end of each calendar year based on FERC Form 1 values to true-up monthly bills for that year to actual FERC Form 1 data. New England Hydro shall also render to each Participant an invoice or notice for its Participating Share of any amounts due under this Agreement (other than monthly Support Charge and the Credit Enhancement Charge) including but not limited to payments to be made under Sections 15, 16, 17, and 20D. Each Participant shall promptly pay to New England Hydro the amount shown on any invoice submitted under this Section. New England Hydro shall date and mail, including delivery by electronic mail, monthly invoices for the Support Charge and Credit Enhancement Charge, if any, on or about the 25th day of the month for the prior month and this invoice shall be due and payable by the 25th day of the coming month and if not paid within that time period shall bear interest compounded quarterly from the first day of the month in which payment is due to the date when payment is made at an annual rate equal to the then-applicable FERC interest rate percentage over the current interest rate on prime commercial loans from time to time in effect (the Base Rate) at the principal office of JPMorgan Chase & Co. Any invoice or notice for payments due under this Agreement (other than a monthly Support Charge and Credit Enhancement Charge invoice), that is not paid when due under this Agreement shall bear interest compounded monthly from the mailing date of the invoice to the date when payment is made at an annual rate equal to two percent (2%) over the Base Rate at the principal office of JPMorgan Chase & Co.
